ated england, ultimately derives name anglia (angeln) peninsula baltic sea. closely related frisian languages, low german (low saxon), german, dutch afrikaans. english vocabulary significantly influenced other germanic languages early medieval period, later romance languages, particularly latin french.[6] english either official language one official languages almost 60 sovereign states. commonly spoken language united kingdom, united states, canada, australia, ireland, new zealand, widely spoken some areas caribbean, africa, south asia.[7] third common native language world, mandarin spanish.[8] widely learned second language official language united nations, european union, many other world regional international organisations. widely spoken germanic language, accounting least 70% speakers indo-european branch. english developed course 1,400 years. earliest forms english, set anglo-frisian dialects brought great britain anglo-saxon settlers fifth century, called old english. middle english began late 11th century norman conquest england, period language influenced french.[9] early modern english began late 15th century introduction printing press london king james bible, start great vowel shift.[10] worldwide influence british empire, modern english spread around world 17th mid-20th centuries. types printed electronic media, well emergence united states global superpower, english become leading language international discourse lingua franca many regions professional contexts science, navigation, law.[11] modern english little inflection compared many other languages, relies auxiliary verbs word order expression complex tenses, aspect mood, well passive constructions, interrogatives some negation. despite noticeable variation among accents dialects english used different countries regions– terms phonetics phonology, sometimes also vocabulary, grammar spelling– english-speakers around world able communicate one another relative ease. contents 1 classification 2 hist