o-germanic. some shared features germanic languages use modal verbs, division verbs strong weak classes, sound changes affecting proto-indo-european consonants, known grimm's verner's laws. grimm's law, word foot begins /f/ germanic languages, cognates other indo-european languages begin /p/. english classified anglo-frisian language frisian english share other features, palatalisation consonants velar consonants proto-germanic (see phonological history old english §palatalization).[18] english sing, sang, sung; dutch zingen, zong, gezongen; german singen, sang, gesungen (strong verb) english laugh, laughed; dutch german lachen, lachte (weak verb) english foot, dutch voet, german fuß, norwegian swedish fot (initial /f/ derived proto-indo-european *p grimm's law) latin pes, stem ped-; modern greek πόδι pódi; russian под pod; sanskrit पद् pád (original proto-indo-european *p) english cheese, frisian tsiis (ch ts palatalisation) german käse dutch kaas (k without palatalisation) english, like other insular germanic languages, icelandic faroese, developed independently continental germanic languages influences. english thus mutually intelligible continental germanic language, differing vocabulary, syntax, phonology, although some, dutch, show strong affinities english, especially earlier stages.[19] english history changed considerably response contact other languages, particularly old norse norman french, some scholars argued english considered mixed language creole– theory called middle english creole hypothesis. although high degree influence languages vocabulary grammar modern english widely acknowledged, specialists language contact consider english true mixed language.[20][21] history main article: history english language proto-germanic old english main article: old english opening old english epic poem beowulf, handwritten half-uncial script: hƿæt ƿē gārde/na ingēar dagum þēod cyninga / þrym ge frunon... "listen! spear-danes days yore heard glory folk-kings..." earliest form english called old english anglo-saxon (c.550–1066ce). old english developed set north sea germanic dialects originally spoken along coasts frisia, lower saxony, jutland, southern sweden germanic tribes known angles, saxons, jutes. fifth century, anglo-saxons settled britain romans withdrew britain. seventh century, germanic language anglo-saxons became dominant britain, replacing languages roman britain (43–409 ce): common brittonic, celtic language, latin, brought britain roman occupation.[22][23][24] england english (originally englaland englisc) named angles.[25] old english divided four dialects: anglian dialects, mercian northumbrian, saxon dialects, kentish west saxon.[26] educational reforms king alfred ninth century influence kingdom wessex, west saxon dialect became standard written variety.[27] epic poem beowulf written west saxon, earliest english poem, cædmon's hymn, written northumbrian.[28] modern english developed mainly mercian, scots language developed northumbrian. short inscriptions early period old english written using runic script.[29] sixth century, latin alphabet adopted, written half-uncial letterforms. included runic letters wynn ⟨ƿ⟩ thorn ⟨þ⟩, modified latin letters eth ⟨ð⟩, ash ⟨æ⟩.[29][30] old english different modern english difficult 21st-century english speakers understand. grammar similar modern german, closest relative old frisian. nouns, adjectives, pronouns, verbs many inflectional endings forms, word order much freer modern english. modern english case forms pronouns (he, him, his) verb endings (i have, has), old english case endings nouns well, verbs person number endings.[31][32][33] translation matthew 8:20 1000ce shows examples case endings (nominative plural, accusative plural, genitive singular) verb ending (present plural): foxas habbað holu heofonan fuglas nest fox-as habb-að hol-u heofon-an fugl-as nest-∅ fox-nom.pl have-prs.pl hole-acc.pl heaven-gen.sg bird-nom.pl nest-acc.pl "foxes holes birds heaven nest