nal system, probably order reconcile old norse old english, inflectionally different morphologically similar. distinction nominative accusative case lost except personal pronouns, instrumental case dropped, use genitive case limited describing possession. inflectional system regularised many irregular inflectional forms,[38] gradually simplified system agreement, making word order less flexible.[39] wycliffe bible 1380s, passage matthew 8:20 written foxis han dennes, briddis heuene han nestis[40] plural suffix -n verb still retained, none case endings nouns present. 12th century middle english fully developed, integrating norse norman features; continued spoken transition early modern english around 1500. middle english literature includes geoffrey chaucer's canterbury tales, malory's le morte d'arthur. middle english period use regional dialects writing proliferated, dialect traits even used effect authors chaucer. early modern english main article: early modern english graphic representation great vowel shift, showing pronunciation long vowels gradually shifted, high vowels i: u: breaking diphthongs lower vowels shifting pronunciation one level next period history english early modern english (1500–1700). early modern english characterised great vowel shift (1350–1700), inflectional simplification, linguistic standardisation. great vowel shift affected stressed long vowels middle english. chain shift, meaning shift triggered subsequent shift vowel system. mid open vowels raised, close vowels broken diphthongs. example, word bite originally pronounced word beet today, second vowel word pronounced word boot today. great vowel shift explains many irregularities spelling, since english retains many spellings middle english, also explains english vowel letters different pronunciations letters other languages.[41][42] english began rise prestige reign henry v. around 1430, court chancery westminster began using english official documents, new standard form middle english, known chancery standard, developed dialects london east midlands. 1476, william caxton introduced printing press england began publishing first printed books london, expanding influence form english.[43] literature early modern period includes works william shakespeare translation bible commissioned king james i. even vowel shift language still sounded different modern english: example, consonant clusters /kn ɡn sw/ knight, gnat, sword still pronounced. many grammatical features modern reader shakespeare might find quaint archaic represent distinct characteristics early modern english.[44] 1611 king james version bible, written early modern english, matthew 8:20 says: foxes haue holes birds ayre haue nests[34] exemplifies loss case effects sentence structure (replacement subject-verb-object word order, use instead non-possessive genitive), introduction loanwords french (ayre) word replacements (bird originally meaning "nestling" replaced oe fugol). spread modern english late 18th century, british empire facilitated spread english colonies geopolitical dominance. commerce, science technology, diplomacy, art, formal education contributed english becoming first truly global language. english also facilitated worldwide international communication.[45][46] england continued form new colonies, turn became independent developed norms speak write language. english adopted north america, india, parts africa, australasia, many other regions. post-colonial period, some newly created nations multiple indigenous languages opted continue using english official language avoid political difficulties inherent promoting one indigenous language others.[47][48][49] 20th century growing economic cultural influence united states status superpower following second world war has, along worldwide broadcasting english bbc[50] other broadcasters, significantly accelerated spread language across planet.[51][52] 21st century, english widely spoken written language ever been.[53] major featur