e ga,[249] rhoticity strongly prevails, replacing region's historical non-rhotic prestige,[250] though social variation may still apply.[251][252] southern accents colloquially described "drawl" "twang,"[253] recognised readily southern vowel shift begins glide-deleting /aɪ/ vowel (e.g. pronouncing spy almost like spa), "southern breaking" several front pure vowels gliding vowel even two syllables (e.g. pronouncing word "press" almost like "pray-us"),[254] pin–pen merger, other distinctive phonologial, grammatical, lexical features, many actually recent developments 19th century later.[255] today spoken primarily working- middle-class african americans, african american vernacular english (aave) also largely non-rhotic likely originated among enslaved africans african americans influenced primarily non-rhotic, non-standard english spoken whites old south. minority linguists,[256] contrarily, propose aave mostly traces back african languages spoken slaves develop pidgin creole english communicate slaves other ethnic linguistic origins.[257] aave shares important commonalities older southern american english probably developed highly coherent homogeneous variety 19th early 20th century. aave commonly stigmatised north america form "broken" "uneducated" english, also common modern southern american english, linguists today recognise fully developed varieties english norms shared large speech community.[258][259] australia new zealand main articles: australian english new zealand english since 1788 english spoken oceania, major native dialect australian english spoken first language vast majority inhabitants australian continent, general australian serving standard accent. english neighbouring new zealand lesser degree become influential standard variety language.[260] australian new zealand english closely related other, followed south african english english south-eastern england, similarly non-rhotic accents, aside some accents south island new zealand. stand innovative vowels: many short vowels fronted raised, whereas many long vowels diphthongised. australian english also contrast long short vowels, found other varieties. australian english grammar differs british american english instances, one difference lack verbal concord collective plural subjects.[261][262] new zealand english differs little australian english, characteristics sets accent apart, use [ʍ] wh- front vowels even closer australian english.[263][264][265] africa, caribbean, south asia see also: south african english, caribbean english, indian english english spoken widely south africa official co-official language several countries. south africa, english spoken since 1820, co-existing afrikaans various african languages khoe bantu languages. today 9 percent south african population speak south african english (sae) first language. sae non-rhotic variety, tends follow rp norm. alone among non-rhotic varieties lacking intrusive r. different l2 varieties differ based native language speakers.[266] phonological differences rp vowels.[267] consonant differences include tendency pronounce /p, t, t͡ʃ, k/ without aspiration (e.g. pin pronounced [pɪn] rather [pʰɪn] other varieties), r often pronounced flap [ɾ] instead common fricative.[268] several varieties english also spoken caribbean islands colonial possessions britain, including jamaica, leeward windward islands trinidad tobago, barbados, cayman islands, belize. areas home local variety english local english based creole, combining english african languages. prominent varieties jamaican english jamaican creole. central america, english based creoles spoken caribbean coasts nicaragua panama. [269] locals often fluent local english variety local creole languages code-switching frequent, indeed another way conceptualise relationship creole standard varieties see spectrum social registers creole forms serving "basilect" rp-like forms serving "acrolect", formal register.[270] caribbean varieties based british english